SIMPLE: chine
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Chine
<hw>Chine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Chink</er>.]</ety> <def>A chink or cleft; a narrow and deep ravine;
<as>as, Shanklin <ex>Chine</ex> in the Isle of Wight, a quarter of a
mile long and 230 feet deep</as>.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧The cottage in a <xex>chine</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>J.
Ingelow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Chine
<hw>Chine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>eschine</ets>,
F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧chine</ets>, fr. OHG. <ets>skina</ets> needle, prickle,
shin, G. <ets>schiene</ets> splint, <ets>schienbein</ets> shin. For the
meaning cf. L. <ets>spina</ets> thorn, prickle, or spine, the backbone.
Cf. <er>Shin</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The backbone or spine of an
animal; the back.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧And <xex>chine</xex> with rising bristles
roughly spread.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A piece of the backbone of an animal, with the
adjoining parts, cut for cooking. <note>[See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Beef</er>.]</note></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The edge or rim of a cask, etc., formed by the
projecting ends of the staves; the chamfered end of a stave.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Chine
<hw>Chine</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Chined</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut
through the backbone of; to cut into chine pieces.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Too chamfer the ends of a stave and form the
chine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chined</ent>⟦br⟧
